rom another tribe trapped in a world where she will always be the outsider. Barbara Fass Leavy believes that, in the societies in which the tale and its variants endured, woman was the other--the outsider trapped in a society that could never be her own. Leavy shows how the tale, though rarely explicitly recognized, is frequently replayed in modern literature. Beautifully written, this book reveals the myriad ways in which the folktales of a society reflect its cultural values, and particularly how folktales are allegories of gender relations. It will interest anyone involved in literary, gender, and cultural studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aMan-woman relationshipsvFolklore. 0aMan-woman relationships. 0aSexvFolklore. 0aSex. 0aSwan maiden (Tale)vClassification. 0aSwan maiden (Tale)xHistory and criticism. 0aSwan maiden (Tale). 0aWomenvFolklore. 0aWomen. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311071692440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814752685.001.0001zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814752685zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814752685/original  a978-3-11-071692-4 New York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA